{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-ab362ffc0684445d", "type": "tool_result", "content": "\\displaystyle=\\mathcal{G}\\bigl(x_{d};\\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\log(\\bm{x}_{\\not d})+c_{d}+1,\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\,\\bm{x}_{\\not d}+b_{d}\\bigr),\n\n (9) \n\nwhere \\mathcal{G}(\\,\\cdot\\,;\\alpha,\\beta) is the gamma distribution with the shape parameter \\alpha and rate \\beta.\n\nAs in Eq. ( 8 ), GammaBM handles the variable in both the linear scale, via \\bm{x}^{\\mathsf{T}}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{x}, and the logarithmic scale, via \\log(\\bm{x})^{\\mathsf{T}}\\mathbf{V}\\log(\\bm{x}).\nIn other words, within a single energy function, it provides a unified modeling framework that captures not only absolute changes in values via linear interactions but also relative, ratio-based scaling via logarithmic interactions.\nThis property of GammaBM is advantageous for audio applications [ 22 ] because human perception handles magnitude of sound in approximate logarithmic scale.\n\n Figure 1 : Graphical representation of (a) standard BM, (b) GaussBM, (c) DUBM, and (d) proposed PolarBM. \n\n III PolarBM and Its Properties \n\nComplex numbers are essential for modeling and analyzing real-world signals and systems.\nHowever, the standard BMs can only handle specific types of variables, e.g., GaussBM for real numbers and DUBM for unimodular complex numbers.\nIn this study, we propose a novel BM that can naturally handle complex numbers in the polar coordinate.\n\n III-A PolarBM \n\nUpon examining the definitions of BM and DUBM in Eqs. ( 2 ) and ( 6 ), it appears that arbitrary complex variables \\bm{z}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D} can be handled by adopting the following definition:\n\n\\displaystyle z_{d}\n\n\\displaystyle=r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{{\\rm i}\\theta_{d}},\\quad r_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0},\\quad\\theta_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi),\n\n (10) \n\n\\displaystyle p(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{-E(\\bm{z})},\n\n (11) \n\n\\displaystyle E(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=-\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}-\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right],\n\n (12) \n\nWhen \\mathbf{W}^{\\sf H}=\\mathbf{W} and {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{W})=\\bm{0} (\\mathbf{W}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D\\times D}), the conditional probability density of a unit z_{d} with given \\bm{z}_{\\not d} is\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}+\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{i=1}^{D}\\sum_{j=1}^{D}\\overline{z}_{i}w_{ij}z_{j}+\\Re\\left[\\sum_{i=1}^{D}\\overline{b}_{i}z_{i}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{i=1}^{D}(\\overline{z}_{i}w_{id}z_{d}+\\overline{z}_{d}\\overline{w}_{id}z_{i})+\\Re\\left[\\overline{b}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}(\\overline{\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}}\\,z_{d}+\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}\\,\\overline{z}_{d})+\\Re\\left[\\overline{b}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\Re\\left[\\overline{\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}}\\,z_{d}\\right]+\\Re\\left[\\overline{b}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\Re\\left[(\\overline{\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}+b_{d}})z_{d}\\right]},\n\n (13) \n\nwhere Z^{\\prime} is the normalization constant independent of z_{d}.\nLet u_{d}=\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d}+b_{d}=a_{d}\\,{\\rm e}^{{\\rm i}\\phi_{d}}, a_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0}, \\phi_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi), then\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\Re\\left[\\overline{u}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n (14) \n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}|z_{d}|\\cos(\\angle z_{d}-\\phi_{d})}.\n\n (15) \n\nThe distribution of magnitude r_{d}=|z_{d}| can be obtained by marginalizing phase \\theta_{d}=\\angle z_{d} in the polar coordinate system, with the variable transformation p(z)\\,\\mathrm{d}z=p(r,\\theta)\\,r\\,\\mathrm{d}r\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta, as\n\n\\displaystyle p(r_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\\,r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta_{d}\n\n (16) \n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{r_{d}}{Z^{\\prime}}\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta_{d}\n\n (17) \n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{2\\pi}{Z^{\\prime}}r_{d}\\,I_{0}(a_{d}\\,r_{d}),\n\n (18) \n\nwhere I_{0}(x) is the modified Bessel function of the first kind of order zero.\nHowever, this probability density diverges when r_{d}\\rightarrow\\infty as r_{d}\\,I_{0}(a_{d}\\,r_{d})\\rightarrow\\infty.\n\nTo introduce decay similar to GaussBM, we propose to restrict {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{W})=-2\\bm{\\beta} with \\beta_{d}>0 (\\forall d).\nThis modification adds -\\beta_{d}\\,\\overline{z}_{d}\\,z_{d}=-\\beta_{d}\\,|z_{d}|^{2} to the exponent of the energy function, and the conditional probability density of z_{d} becomes\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}|z_{d}|^{2}+a_{d}|z_{d}|\\cos(\\angle z_{d}-\\phi_{d})}.\n\n (19) \n\nIts marginalization over the phase \\theta_{d} gives the following distribution for the magnitude r_{d},\n\n\\displaystyle p(r_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{r_{d}}{Z^{\\prime}}\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}r_{d}^{2}+a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta_{d}\n\n (20) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}r_{d}^{2}}I_{0}(a_{d}\\,r_{d})\n\n (21) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto{\\rm Rice}\\Bigl(r_{d};\\frac{a_{d}}{2\\beta},\\frac{1}{\\beta}\\Bigr),\n\n (22) \n\nwhere {\\rm Rice}(\\,\\cdot\\,;\\nu,\\sigma^{2}) is the Rician distribution 1 1 1 Note that the Rician distribution is usually defined as {\\rm Rice}(r;\\nu,\\sigma^{2})=\\frac{r}{\\sigma^{2}}{\\rm e}^{-{(r^{2}+\\nu^{2})}/{2\\sigma^{2}}}I_{0}(\\frac{r\\nu}{\\sigma^{2}}).\nIn this paper, to focus on the complex number system, we define it as {\\rm Rice}(r;\\nu,\\sigma^{2})=\\frac{2r}{\\sigma^{2}}{\\rm e}^{-{(r^{2}+\\nu^{2})}/{\\sigma^{2}}}I_{0}(\\frac{2r\\nu}{\\sigma^{2}}) so that the variance of a complex-valued variable z becomes \\sigma^{2} (i.e., the variance \\sigma^{2} is 1/2 of that in the usual definition). \nwith the noncentrality parameter \\nu and variance \\sigma^{2}.\nMoreover, when the magnitude is known, the conditional probability distribution of z_{d} becomes the von Mises distribution as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p(\\theta_{d}\\,|\\,r_{d},\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\n\n (23) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{VM}\\bigl(\\theta_{d};\\phi_{d},a_{d}\\,r_{d}\\bigr),\n\n (24) \n\nAs in Eqs. ( 19 ) and ( 24 ), the phase and magnitude are not independent; instead, the concentration parameter of phase is proportional to the magnitude r_{d}.\nThis is consistent with the intuition regarding the complex spectrum of a speech signal.\nThe phase spreads uniformly (becoming uncertain) when the magnitude is small, such as in silent intervals, whereas the phase becomes deterministic when a strong magnitude is observed, such as in voiced intervals. That is, a probabilistic model for complex-valued variables suitable for audio signals can be naturally obtained by this formulation.\nWe propose BM based on Eq. ( 19 ) and name it PolarBM to capture the relationships among complex-valued units, where phase and amplitude are interdependent.\n\nIn summary, the proposed PolarBM is defined as\n\n\\displaystyle z_{d}\n\n\\displaystyle=r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{{\\rm i}\\theta_{d}},\\quad r_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0},\\quad\\theta_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi),\n\n (25) \n\n\\displaystyle p(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{-E_{\\rm Polar}(\\bm{z})},\n\n (26) \n\n\\displaystyle E_{\\rm Polar}(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=-\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}-\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right],\n\n (27) \n\nwhere Z=\\int p(\\bm{z})\\,\\mathrm{d}\\bm{z} is the normalization term, and the model parameters are \\mathbf{W}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D\\times D} (\\mathbf{W}^{\\sf H}=\\mathbf{W}, {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{W})=-2\\bm{\\beta}, \\beta_{d}>0) and \\bm{b}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D}.\nFig.  1 illustrates the differences between the proposed PolarBM and other existing BMs, including binary BM, GaussBM, and DUBM.\nWhile all the models describe interactions between two units, they differ in the respective domains.\nNote that, when r_{d}=1 and \\beta_{d}\\rightarrow 0 (\\forall d), then PolarBM becomes p(\\theta_{d}\\,|\\,r_{d}=1,\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})=\\mathcal{VM}(\\theta_{d};\\alpha_{d},a_{d}), which is the same as DUBM.\nMoreover, when all of \\bm{z}, \\mathbf{W} and \\bm{b} are real-valued, then PolarBM coincides with GaussBM.\nTherefore, the proposed PolarBM can be regarded as a natural extention of the existing BMs.\n\n Figure 2 : Conceptual diagram of the proposed LogPolarBM, which combines the complex-valued representation of PolarBM with the log-amplitude representation capability of GammaBM to capture diverse audio characteristics. \n\n III-B LogPolarBM \n\nThe conditional probability density of the unit z_{d} in Eq. ( 19 ) can be interpreted as follows.\nWhen Eq. ( 19 ) is expressed using the Cartesian coordinate system z_{d}=x_{d}+{\\rm i}y_{d} (x_{d},\\,y_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}), it can be rewritten as a circularly symmetric (isotropic) complex normal distribution as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}r_{d}^{2}+a_{d}r_{d}(\\cos\\theta_{d}\\cos\\phi_{d}+\\sin\\theta_{d}\\sin\\phi_{d})}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}(x_{d}^{2}+y_{d}^{2})+\\Re[u_{d}]x_{d}+\\Im[u_{d}]y_{d}}\n\n (28) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}\\left[\\left(x_{d}-\\frac{\\Re[u_{d}]}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right)^{2}+\\left(y_{d}-\\frac{\\Im[u_{d}]}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right)^{2}\\right]}\n\n (29) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}\\left|z_{d}-\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right|^{2}}\n\n (30) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{c}}\\Bigl(z_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}}\\Bigr),\n\n (31) \n\nwhere the complex normal distribution with mean \\mu\\in\\mathbb{C} and variance \\sigma^{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} is given by\n\n\\displaystyle\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{c}}(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2})=\\frac{1}{\\pi\\sigma^{2}}{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{|z-\\mu|^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}}.\n\n (32) \n\nThis indicates that PolarBM proposed in the previous subsection handles only linear relationships between the units.\nHowever, such a simple model may not be suitable for representation of audio signals (such as speech) because the human auditory system perceives the magnitude of audio signals with a logarithmic-like scale.\n\nIn this subsection, we further propose LogPolarBM, a variant of PolarBM integrated with GammaBM for the logarithmic representation of magnitude spectra, as illustrated in Fig.  2 .\nWe define the LogPolarBM as\n\n\\displaystyle z_{d}=\n\n\\displaystyle r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{{\\rm i}\\theta_{d}},\\quad r_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0},\\quad\\theta_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi),\n\n (33) \n\n\\displaystyle p(\\bm{z})=\n\n\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{-E_{\\rm LogPolar}(\\bm{z})},\n\n (34) \n\n\\displaystyle E_{\\rm LogPolar}(\\bm{z})=\n\n\\displaystyle-\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}-\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right]\n\n\\displaystyle-\\frac{1}{2}\\log|\\bm{z}|{{}^{\\sf T}}\\mathbf{V}\\log|\\bm{z}|-\\bm{c}^{\\sf T}\\log|\\bm{z}|,\n\n (35) \n\nwhere \\mathbf{V}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{D\\times D} (\\mathbf{V}^{\\sf T}=\\mathbf{V}, {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{V})=\\bm{0}) and \\bm{c}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{D} are the parameters related to the logarithmic magnitude spectra, which must satisfy \\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\log|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}|+c_{d}>-2 (\\forall d) for \\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{D-1}.\nThis is a natual combination of PolarBM in Eq. ( 27 ) and GammaBM in Eq. ( 8 ).\nCompared to PolarBM in Eq. ( 27 ), this LogPolarBM adds logarithmic amplitude terms.\nBy employing this logarithmic representation, LogPolarBM effectively captures perceptually relevant features, consistent with human auditory perception.\nNote that PolarBM in Eq. ( 27 ) is the special case of LogPolarBM in Eq. ( 35 ) when \\mathbf{V}=\\mathbf{O} and \\bm{c}=\\bm{0} (\\forall d, \\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\log|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}|+c_{d}=0).\n\nFor LogPolarBM, the conditional probability density of a unit z_{d} can be written as\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}|\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto|z_{d}|^{2\\alpha_{d}-2}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}|z_{d}|^{2}+a_{d}|z_{d}|\\cos(\\angle z_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\n\n (36) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto|z_{d}|^{2\\alpha_{d}-2}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}\\left|z_{d}-\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right|^{2}}\n\n (37) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}\\Bigl(z_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}},\\alpha_{d}\\Bigr),\n\n (38) \n\nwhere \\alpha_{d}=(\\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}\\log|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}|+c_{d})/2+1 (>0), and \\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}(z) is the following distribution termed the power-weighted noncentral complex Gaussian (PW-NCCG) distribution :\n\n\\displaystyle\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}\\bigl(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2},\\alpha\\bigr)=\\frac{|z|^{2\\alpha-2}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{|z-\\mu|^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}}}{\\pi\\,\\sigma^{2\\alpha}\\,\\Gamma(\\alpha)\\,L_{\\alpha-1}(-\\frac{|\\mu|^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}})},\n\n (39) \n\nwhere \\Gamma(\\cdot) is the gamma function, L_{n}(\\cdot) is the nth-order Laguerre function, and \\mu\\in\\mathbb{C}, \\sigma^{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} and \\alpha\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} are the mean (center of gravity), variance, and degree parameters, respectively.\nThe degree parameter \\alpha governs the shape of the distribution (note that PW-NCCG reduces to the complex normal distribution when \\alpha=1, i.e., \\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2},1)=\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{c}}(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2})).\nIn particular, a value of 0<\\alpha<1 concentrates the probability density around the origin.\nThis is an advantageous property for representing spectra of sparse signals such as vowels, as it can capture sharp spectral peaks with a heavier-tailed distribution.\nOn the other hand, a value of \\alpha>1 suppresses the density around the origin.\nIn this case, it well represents spectra of more complex signals such as fricative sounds that tend to exhibit more diffuse energy distributions, as it approaches a Gaussian-like distribution with a lighter tail.\nTherefore, LogPolarBM (based on PW-NCCG) provides greater flexibility in modeling a wider range of audio signals than the standard complex normal distribution-based PolarBM, thanks to the additional parameter \\alpha.\nSome more details on PW-NCCG can be found in [ 25 ] .\n\nSimilar to that of PolarBM, given the magnitude r_{d}, the conditional probability density of a unit z_{d} for LogPolarBM is the following von Mises distribution:\n\n\\displaystyle p(\\theta_{d}|r_{d},\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\n\n (40) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{VM}\\bigl(\\theta_{d};\\phi_{d},a_{d}\\,r_{d}\\bigr).\n\n (41) \n\nOn the other hand, the distribution of magnitude, p(r_{d}|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}), is calculated as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p(r_{d}|\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}\\Bigl(z_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}},\\alpha_{d}\\Bigr)\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta\n\n (42) \n\n\\displaystyle=p\\Bigl(r_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}},\\alpha_{d}\\Bigr),\n\n (43) \n\nwhere the last term is given by\n\n\\displaystyle p(r;\\nu,\\sigma^{2},\\alpha)=\\frac{2\\,r^{2\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}+\\nu^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}}\\,I_{0}\\!\\left(\\frac{2\\nu r}{\\sigma^{2}}\\right)}{\\sigma^{2\\alpha}\\,\\Gamma(\\alpha)\\,L_{\\alpha-1}\\!\\left(-\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}\\right)}.\n\n (44) \n\nThis is an extension of the Rician distribution that can be derived from PolarBM (when \\alpha=1, it coincides with the Rician distribution; see Eq. (9) in  [ 25 ] ).\nThis distribution can also be interpreted as a generalization of several other magnitude or power distributions, highlighting the versatility and effectiveness of LogPolarBM based on this distribution.\nWe will summarize these relationships in the next subsection.\n\n III-C Relationship of Eq. ( 44 ) to Existing Distributions \n\nThe magnitude distribution in Eq. ( 44 ) is related to the other standard distributions as follows.\n\nWhen \\nu=0, \\sigma^{2}=\\frac{\\Omega}{\\alpha} and \\Omega>0, Eq. ( 44 ) becomes the Nakagami distribution as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p\\Bigl(r;0,\\frac{\\Omega}{\\alpha},\\alpha\\Bigr)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{2\\,\\alpha^{\\alpha}\\,r^{2\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{\\alpha}{\\Omega}r^{2}}}{\\Omega^{\\alpha}\\,\\Gamma(\\alpha)}\n\n (45) \n\n\\displaystyle={\\rm Nakagami}\\bigl(r;\\alpha,\\Omega\\bigr).\n\n (46) \n\nTherefore, Eq. ( 44 ) can be viewed as a generalization of the Nakagami distribution.\nAlthough the distribution in Eq. ( 44 ) is naturally derived from the energy function in Eq. ( 35 ), these relationships to the Rice and Nakagami distributions suggest its appropriateness, given their widespread application in Telecommunications Engineering.\n\nWhen \\sigma^{2}=2, \\alpha=\\frac{k}{2} and k>0, Eq. ( 44 ) can be rewritten as the noncentral chi distribution:\n\n\\displaystyle p\\Bigl(r;\\nu,2,\\frac{k}{2}\\Bigr)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{2^{1-\\frac{k}{2}}\\,r^{k-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}+\\nu^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{0}(\\nu\\,r)}{\\Gamma(\\frac{k}{2})\\,L_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(-\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})}\n\n (47) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto r^{k-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{0}(\\nu\\,r),\n\n (48) \n\nwhere the noncentral chi distribution is given by\n\n\\displaystyle\\chi^{\\prime}(r;k,\\nu)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\nu^{1-\\frac{k}{2}}\\,r^{\\frac{k}{2}}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}+\\nu^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(\\nu\\,r)\n\n (49) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto r^{\\frac{k}{2}}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(\\nu\\,r)\n\n (50) \n\nfor k=2 (in this case, it is the Rician distribution as well).\nNote that the order of the modified Bessel function is always 0 in Eq. ( 44 ) (i.e., I_{0}), while that of the noncentral chi distribution depends on the exponent of r.\nThis difference is more apparent by rewriting Eq. ( 50 ) as\n\n\\displaystyle\\chi^{\\prime}(r;k,\\nu)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2}}(\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})^{n}}{n!}\\,\\frac{r^{2n+k-1}\\,{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}}{2^{n+\\frac{k}{2}-1}\\,\\Gamma(n+\\frac{k}{2})}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}{\\rm Poisson}\\Bigl(n;\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2}\\Bigr)\\,\\chi\\bigl(r;2n+k\\bigr),\n\n (51) \n\nwhere {\\rm Poisson}(\\,\\cdot\\,;\\lambda) is the Poisson distribution, \\chi(\\,\\cdot\\,;k) is the chi distribution, and I_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(x)=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{1}{n!\\,\\Gamma(n+\\frac{k}{2})}(\\frac{x}{2})^{2n+\\frac{k}{2}-1} is used.\nIt indicates that the noncentral chi distribution is a mixture distribution of the chi distribution whose parameter n is determined by the Poisson distribution.\nOn the other hand, Eq. ( 47 ) can be rewritten as\n\n\\displaystyle p(r;\\nu,2,\\frac{k}{2})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{(\\frac{k}{2})_{n}\\,(\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})^{n}}{n!^{2}\\,L_{-\\frac{k}{2}}(\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})}\\,\\frac{r^{2n+k-1}\\,{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}}{2^{n+\\frac{k}{2}-1}\\,\\Gamma(n+\\frac{k}{2})}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}{\\rm Poisson^{\\prime}}\\Bigl(n;\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2},\\frac{k}{2}\\Bigr)\\,\\chi\\bigl(r;2n+k\\bigr),\n\n (52) \n\nwhere (\\cdot)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol,\n\n\\displaystyle{\\rm Poisson^{\\prime}}(n;\\lambda,\\alpha)=\\frac{(\\alpha)_{n}\\,\\lambda^{n}}{n!^{2}\\,L_{-\\alpha}(\\lambda)},\n\n (53) \n\nand I_{0}(x)=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{1}{n!\\,\\Gamma(n+1)}(\\frac{x}{2})^{2n} is used.\nThe modified Poisson distribution in Eq. ( 53 ) is skewed according to the parameter \\alpha, where \\alpha=1 reduces to the Poisson distribution.\nTherefore, the noncentral chi distribution and Eq. ( 44 ) can be interpreted as the marginal distribution of a chi distribution whose degrees of freedom are incremented by a random non-negative integer obaying the discrete (Poisson or modified Poisson) distributions.\n\nFurthermore, by writing the inverse variance (rate) and noncentrality as \\beta=\\frac{1}{\\sigma^{2}}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} and \\lambda=\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}=\\beta\\,|\\mu|^{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{\\geq 0}, respectively, and viewing as a distribution for power x=r^{2}, Eq. ( 44 ) can be rewritten as\n\n\\displaystyle p(x;\\alpha,\\beta,\\lambda)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{\\beta^{\\alpha}}{\\Gamma(\\alpha)\\,L_{-\\alpha}(\\lambda)}\\,x^{\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta x}\\,I_{0}(2\\sqrt{\\beta\\,\\lambda\\,x}),\n\n (54) \n\nwhich reduces to the gamma distribution,\n\n\\displaystyle{\\rm Gamma}(x;\\alpha,\\beta)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{\\beta^{\\alpha}}{\\Gamma(\\alpha)}\\,x^{\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta x},\n\n (55) \n\nwhen \\lambda=0.\nTherefore, Eq. ( 44 ) is also a generalization of the gamma distribution.\nIn other words, the gamma distribution can be viewed as a distribution of magnitude of PW-NCCG centered at the origin (\\lambda=\\nu=\\mu=0).\nUsing the modified Poisson distribution in Eq. ( 53 ), Eq. ( 54 ) can be written as\n\n\\displaystyle p(x;\\alpha,\\beta,\\lambda)=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}{\\rm Poisson^{\\prime}}(n;\\lambda,\\alpha)\\,{\\rm Gamma}(x;n+\\alpha,\\beta),\n\n (56) \n\nwhich indicates that the proposed distribution can be interpreted as a mixture distribution of the gamma and modified Poisson distributions.\nAlthough the distributions for magnitude in Eq. ( 44 ) and for power in Eq. ( 54 ) are essentially the same, we will only consider Eq. ( 54 ) hereafter because of its simplicity.\nFurther statistical properties of this distribution, such as the mean, variance, and kurtosis, as well as detailed comparisons are provided in [ 25 ] .\n\n IV PolarRBM and LogPolarRBM \n\nSimilar to standard BMs, the representational capacity of PolarBM can be significantly enhanced by introducing hidden units.", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "f3ce64ae-334a-4dd6-b609-bf97227701f9", "uuid": "77d43210-dfc5-44f4-b710-02582af271c8", "timestamp": "2026-07-15T07:00:14.242Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "\\displaystyle=\\mathcal{G}\\bigl(x_{d};\\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\log(\\bm{x}_{\\not d})+c_{d}+1,\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\,\\bm{x}_{\\not d}+b_{d}\\bigr),\n\n (9) \n\nwhere \\mathcal{G}(\\,\\cdot\\,;\\alpha,\\beta) is the gamma distribution with the shape parameter \\alpha and rate \\beta.\n\nAs in Eq. ( 8 ), GammaBM handles the variable in both the linear scale, via \\bm{x}^{\\mathsf{T}}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{x}, and the logarithmic scale, via \\log(\\bm{x})^{\\mathsf{T}}\\mathbf{V}\\log(\\bm{x}).\nIn other words, within a single energy function, it provides a unified modeling framework that captures not only absolute changes in values via linear interactions but also relative, ratio-based scaling via logarithmic interactions.\nThis property of GammaBM is advantageous for audio applications [ 22 ] because human perception handles magnitude of sound in approximate logarithmic scale.\n\n Figure 1 : Graphical representation of (a) standard BM, (b) GaussBM, (c) DUBM, and (d) proposed PolarBM. \n\n III PolarBM and Its Properties \n\nComplex numbers are essential for modeling and analyzing real-world signals and systems.\nHowever, the standard BMs can only handle specific types of variables, e.g., GaussBM for real numbers and DUBM for unimodular complex numbers.\nIn this study, we propose a novel BM that can naturally handle complex numbers in the polar coordinate.\n\n III-A PolarBM \n\nUpon examining the definitions of BM and DUBM in Eqs. ( 2 ) and ( 6 ), it appears that arbitrary complex variables \\bm{z}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D} can be handled by adopting the following definition:\n\n\\displaystyle z_{d}\n\n\\displaystyle=r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{{\\rm i}\\theta_{d}},\\quad r_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0},\\quad\\theta_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi),\n\n (10) \n\n\\displaystyle p(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{-E(\\bm{z})},\n\n (11) \n\n\\displaystyle E(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=-\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}-\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right],\n\n (12) \n\nWhen \\mathbf{W}^{\\sf H}=\\mathbf{W} and {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{W})=\\bm{0} (\\mathbf{W}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D\\times D}), the conditional probability density of a unit z_{d} with given \\bm{z}_{\\not d} is\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}+\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{i=1}^{D}\\sum_{j=1}^{D}\\overline{z}_{i}w_{ij}z_{j}+\\Re\\left[\\sum_{i=1}^{D}\\overline{b}_{i}z_{i}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}\\sum_{i=1}^{D}(\\overline{z}_{i}w_{id}z_{d}+\\overline{z}_{d}\\overline{w}_{id}z_{i})+\\Re\\left[\\overline{b}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{1}{2}(\\overline{\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}}\\,z_{d}+\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}\\,\\overline{z}_{d})+\\Re\\left[\\overline{b}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\Re\\left[\\overline{\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}}\\,z_{d}\\right]+\\Re\\left[\\overline{b}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\Re\\left[(\\overline{\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}_{\\not d}+b_{d}})z_{d}\\right]},\n\n (13) \n\nwhere Z^{\\prime} is the normalization constant independent of z_{d}.\nLet u_{d}=\\mathbf{W}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf H}\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d}+b_{d}=a_{d}\\,{\\rm e}^{{\\rm i}\\phi_{d}}, a_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0}, \\phi_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi), then\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{\\Re\\left[\\overline{u}_{d}z_{d}\\right]}\n\n (14) \n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}|z_{d}|\\cos(\\angle z_{d}-\\phi_{d})}.\n\n (15) \n\nThe distribution of magnitude r_{d}=|z_{d}| can be obtained by marginalizing phase \\theta_{d}=\\angle z_{d} in the polar coordinate system, with the variable transformation p(z)\\,\\mathrm{d}z=p(r,\\theta)\\,r\\,\\mathrm{d}r\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta, as\n\n\\displaystyle p(r_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\\,r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta_{d}\n\n (16) \n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{r_{d}}{Z^{\\prime}}\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta_{d}\n\n (17) \n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{2\\pi}{Z^{\\prime}}r_{d}\\,I_{0}(a_{d}\\,r_{d}),\n\n (18) \n\nwhere I_{0}(x) is the modified Bessel function of the first kind of order zero.\nHowever, this probability density diverges when r_{d}\\rightarrow\\infty as r_{d}\\,I_{0}(a_{d}\\,r_{d})\\rightarrow\\infty.\n\nTo introduce decay similar to GaussBM, we propose to restrict {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{W})=-2\\bm{\\beta} with \\beta_{d}>0 (\\forall d).\nThis modification adds -\\beta_{d}\\,\\overline{z}_{d}\\,z_{d}=-\\beta_{d}\\,|z_{d}|^{2} to the exponent of the energy function, and the conditional probability density of z_{d} becomes\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z^{\\prime}}\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}|z_{d}|^{2}+a_{d}|z_{d}|\\cos(\\angle z_{d}-\\phi_{d})}.\n\n (19) \n\nIts marginalization over the phase \\theta_{d} gives the following distribution for the magnitude r_{d},\n\n\\displaystyle p(r_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{r_{d}}{Z^{\\prime}}\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}r_{d}^{2}+a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta_{d}\n\n (20) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}r_{d}^{2}}I_{0}(a_{d}\\,r_{d})\n\n (21) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto{\\rm Rice}\\Bigl(r_{d};\\frac{a_{d}}{2\\beta},\\frac{1}{\\beta}\\Bigr),\n\n (22) \n\nwhere {\\rm Rice}(\\,\\cdot\\,;\\nu,\\sigma^{2}) is the Rician distribution 1 1 1 Note that the Rician distribution is usually defined as {\\rm Rice}(r;\\nu,\\sigma^{2})=\\frac{r}{\\sigma^{2}}{\\rm e}^{-{(r^{2}+\\nu^{2})}/{2\\sigma^{2}}}I_{0}(\\frac{r\\nu}{\\sigma^{2}}).\nIn this paper, to focus on the complex number system, we define it as {\\rm Rice}(r;\\nu,\\sigma^{2})=\\frac{2r}{\\sigma^{2}}{\\rm e}^{-{(r^{2}+\\nu^{2})}/{\\sigma^{2}}}I_{0}(\\frac{2r\\nu}{\\sigma^{2}}) so that the variance of a complex-valued variable z becomes \\sigma^{2} (i.e., the variance \\sigma^{2} is 1/2 of that in the usual definition). \nwith the noncentrality parameter \\nu and variance \\sigma^{2}.\nMoreover, when the magnitude is known, the conditional probability distribution of z_{d} becomes the von Mises distribution as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p(\\theta_{d}\\,|\\,r_{d},\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\n\n (23) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{VM}\\bigl(\\theta_{d};\\phi_{d},a_{d}\\,r_{d}\\bigr),\n\n (24) \n\nAs in Eqs. ( 19 ) and ( 24 ), the phase and magnitude are not independent; instead, the concentration parameter of phase is proportional to the magnitude r_{d}.\nThis is consistent with the intuition regarding the complex spectrum of a speech signal.\nThe phase spreads uniformly (becoming uncertain) when the magnitude is small, such as in silent intervals, whereas the phase becomes deterministic when a strong magnitude is observed, such as in voiced intervals. That is, a probabilistic model for complex-valued variables suitable for audio signals can be naturally obtained by this formulation.\nWe propose BM based on Eq. ( 19 ) and name it PolarBM to capture the relationships among complex-valued units, where phase and amplitude are interdependent.\n\nIn summary, the proposed PolarBM is defined as\n\n\\displaystyle z_{d}\n\n\\displaystyle=r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{{\\rm i}\\theta_{d}},\\quad r_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0},\\quad\\theta_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi),\n\n (25) \n\n\\displaystyle p(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{-E_{\\rm Polar}(\\bm{z})},\n\n (26) \n\n\\displaystyle E_{\\rm Polar}(\\bm{z})\n\n\\displaystyle=-\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}-\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right],\n\n (27) \n\nwhere Z=\\int p(\\bm{z})\\,\\mathrm{d}\\bm{z} is the normalization term, and the model parameters are \\mathbf{W}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D\\times D} (\\mathbf{W}^{\\sf H}=\\mathbf{W}, {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{W})=-2\\bm{\\beta}, \\beta_{d}>0) and \\bm{b}\\in\\mathbb{C}^{D}.\nFig.  1 illustrates the differences between the proposed PolarBM and other existing BMs, including binary BM, GaussBM, and DUBM.\nWhile all the models describe interactions between two units, they differ in the respective domains.\nNote that, when r_{d}=1 and \\beta_{d}\\rightarrow 0 (\\forall d), then PolarBM becomes p(\\theta_{d}\\,|\\,r_{d}=1,\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})=\\mathcal{VM}(\\theta_{d};\\alpha_{d},a_{d}), which is the same as DUBM.\nMoreover, when all of \\bm{z}, \\mathbf{W} and \\bm{b} are real-valued, then PolarBM coincides with GaussBM.\nTherefore, the proposed PolarBM can be regarded as a natural extention of the existing BMs.\n\n Figure 2 : Conceptual diagram of the proposed LogPolarBM, which combines the complex-valued representation of PolarBM with the log-amplitude representation capability of GammaBM to capture diverse audio characteristics. \n\n III-B LogPolarBM \n\nThe conditional probability density of the unit z_{d} in Eq. ( 19 ) can be interpreted as follows.\nWhen Eq. ( 19 ) is expressed using the Cartesian coordinate system z_{d}=x_{d}+{\\rm i}y_{d} (x_{d},\\,y_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}), it can be rewritten as a circularly symmetric (isotropic) complex normal distribution as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}\\,|\\,\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}r_{d}^{2}+a_{d}r_{d}(\\cos\\theta_{d}\\cos\\phi_{d}+\\sin\\theta_{d}\\sin\\phi_{d})}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}(x_{d}^{2}+y_{d}^{2})+\\Re[u_{d}]x_{d}+\\Im[u_{d}]y_{d}}\n\n (28) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}\\left[\\left(x_{d}-\\frac{\\Re[u_{d}]}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right)^{2}+\\left(y_{d}-\\frac{\\Im[u_{d}]}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right)^{2}\\right]}\n\n (29) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}\\left|z_{d}-\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right|^{2}}\n\n (30) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{c}}\\Bigl(z_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}}\\Bigr),\n\n (31) \n\nwhere the complex normal distribution with mean \\mu\\in\\mathbb{C} and variance \\sigma^{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} is given by\n\n\\displaystyle\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{c}}(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2})=\\frac{1}{\\pi\\sigma^{2}}{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{|z-\\mu|^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}}.\n\n (32) \n\nThis indicates that PolarBM proposed in the previous subsection handles only linear relationships between the units.\nHowever, such a simple model may not be suitable for representation of audio signals (such as speech) because the human auditory system perceives the magnitude of audio signals with a logarithmic-like scale.\n\nIn this subsection, we further propose LogPolarBM, a variant of PolarBM integrated with GammaBM for the logarithmic representation of magnitude spectra, as illustrated in Fig.  2 .\nWe define the LogPolarBM as\n\n\\displaystyle z_{d}=\n\n\\displaystyle r_{d}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{{\\rm i}\\theta_{d}},\\quad r_{d}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0},\\quad\\theta_{d}\\in[-\\pi,\\pi),\n\n (33) \n\n\\displaystyle p(\\bm{z})=\n\n\\displaystyle\\frac{1}{Z}\\mathrm{e}^{-E_{\\rm LogPolar}(\\bm{z})},\n\n (34) \n\n\\displaystyle E_{\\rm LogPolar}(\\bm{z})=\n\n\\displaystyle-\\frac{1}{2}\\bm{z}^{\\sf H}\\mathbf{W}\\bm{z}-\\Re\\left[\\bm{b}^{\\sf H}\\bm{z}\\right]\n\n\\displaystyle-\\frac{1}{2}\\log|\\bm{z}|{{}^{\\sf T}}\\mathbf{V}\\log|\\bm{z}|-\\bm{c}^{\\sf T}\\log|\\bm{z}|,\n\n (35) \n\nwhere \\mathbf{V}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{D\\times D} (\\mathbf{V}^{\\sf T}=\\mathbf{V}, {\\rm diag}(\\mathbf{V})=\\bm{0}) and \\bm{c}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{D} are the parameters related to the logarithmic magnitude spectra, which must satisfy \\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\log|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}|+c_{d}>-2 (\\forall d) for \\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}\\in\\mathbb{R}^{D-1}.\nThis is a natual combination of PolarBM in Eq. ( 27 ) and GammaBM in Eq. ( 8 ).\nCompared to PolarBM in Eq. ( 27 ), this LogPolarBM adds logarithmic amplitude terms.\nBy employing this logarithmic representation, LogPolarBM effectively captures perceptually relevant features, consistent with human auditory perception.\nNote that PolarBM in Eq. ( 27 ) is the special case of LogPolarBM in Eq. ( 35 ) when \\mathbf{V}=\\mathbf{O} and \\bm{c}=\\bm{0} (\\forall d, \\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}^{\\sf T}\\log|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}|+c_{d}=0).\n\nFor LogPolarBM, the conditional probability density of a unit z_{d} can be written as\n\n\\displaystyle p(z_{d}|\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto|z_{d}|^{2\\alpha_{d}-2}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}|z_{d}|^{2}+a_{d}|z_{d}|\\cos(\\angle z_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\n\n (36) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto|z_{d}|^{2\\alpha_{d}-2}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta_{d}\\left|z_{d}-\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}}\\right|^{2}}\n\n (37) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}\\Bigl(z_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}},\\alpha_{d}\\Bigr),\n\n (38) \n\nwhere \\alpha_{d}=(\\mathbf{V}_{\\!\\not d,d}\\log|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}|+c_{d})/2+1 (>0), and \\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}(z) is the following distribution termed the power-weighted noncentral complex Gaussian (PW-NCCG) distribution :\n\n\\displaystyle\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}\\bigl(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2},\\alpha\\bigr)=\\frac{|z|^{2\\alpha-2}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{|z-\\mu|^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}}}{\\pi\\,\\sigma^{2\\alpha}\\,\\Gamma(\\alpha)\\,L_{\\alpha-1}(-\\frac{|\\mu|^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}})},\n\n (39) \n\nwhere \\Gamma(\\cdot) is the gamma function, L_{n}(\\cdot) is the nth-order Laguerre function, and \\mu\\in\\mathbb{C}, \\sigma^{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} and \\alpha\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} are the mean (center of gravity), variance, and degree parameters, respectively.\nThe degree parameter \\alpha governs the shape of the distribution (note that PW-NCCG reduces to the complex normal distribution when \\alpha=1, i.e., \\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2},1)=\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{c}}(z;\\mu,\\sigma^{2})).\nIn particular, a value of 0<\\alpha<1 concentrates the probability density around the origin.\nThis is an advantageous property for representing spectra of sparse signals such as vowels, as it can capture sharp spectral peaks with a heavier-tailed distribution.\nOn the other hand, a value of \\alpha>1 suppresses the density around the origin.\nIn this case, it well represents spectra of more complex signals such as fricative sounds that tend to exhibit more diffuse energy distributions, as it approaches a Gaussian-like distribution with a lighter tail.\nTherefore, LogPolarBM (based on PW-NCCG) provides greater flexibility in modeling a wider range of audio signals than the standard complex normal distribution-based PolarBM, thanks to the additional parameter \\alpha.\nSome more details on PW-NCCG can be found in [ 25 ] .\n\nSimilar to that of PolarBM, given the magnitude r_{d}, the conditional probability density of a unit z_{d} for LogPolarBM is the following von Mises distribution:\n\n\\displaystyle p(\\theta_{d}|r_{d},\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathrm{e}^{a_{d}r_{d}\\cos(\\theta_{d}-\\phi_{d})}\n\n (40) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto\\mathcal{VM}\\bigl(\\theta_{d};\\phi_{d},a_{d}\\,r_{d}\\bigr).\n\n (41) \n\nOn the other hand, the distribution of magnitude, p(r_{d}|\\bm{z}_{\\not d}), is calculated as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p(r_{d}|\\bm{z}_{\\not d})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi}\\mathcal{N}_{\\mathrm{pw}}\\Bigl(z_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}},\\alpha_{d}\\Bigr)\\,\\mathrm{d}\\theta\n\n (42) \n\n\\displaystyle=p\\Bigl(r_{d};\\frac{u_{d}}{2\\beta_{d}},\\frac{1}{\\beta_{d}},\\alpha_{d}\\Bigr),\n\n (43) \n\nwhere the last term is given by\n\n\\displaystyle p(r;\\nu,\\sigma^{2},\\alpha)=\\frac{2\\,r^{2\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}+\\nu^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}}\\,I_{0}\\!\\left(\\frac{2\\nu r}{\\sigma^{2}}\\right)}{\\sigma^{2\\alpha}\\,\\Gamma(\\alpha)\\,L_{\\alpha-1}\\!\\left(-\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}\\right)}.\n\n (44) \n\nThis is an extension of the Rician distribution that can be derived from PolarBM (when \\alpha=1, it coincides with the Rician distribution; see Eq. (9) in  [ 25 ] ).\nThis distribution can also be interpreted as a generalization of several other magnitude or power distributions, highlighting the versatility and effectiveness of LogPolarBM based on this distribution.\nWe will summarize these relationships in the next subsection.\n\n III-C Relationship of Eq. ( 44 ) to Existing Distributions \n\nThe magnitude distribution in Eq. ( 44 ) is related to the other standard distributions as follows.\n\nWhen \\nu=0, \\sigma^{2}=\\frac{\\Omega}{\\alpha} and \\Omega>0, Eq. ( 44 ) becomes the Nakagami distribution as follows:\n\n\\displaystyle p\\Bigl(r;0,\\frac{\\Omega}{\\alpha},\\alpha\\Bigr)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{2\\,\\alpha^{\\alpha}\\,r^{2\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{\\alpha}{\\Omega}r^{2}}}{\\Omega^{\\alpha}\\,\\Gamma(\\alpha)}\n\n (45) \n\n\\displaystyle={\\rm Nakagami}\\bigl(r;\\alpha,\\Omega\\bigr).\n\n (46) \n\nTherefore, Eq. ( 44 ) can be viewed as a generalization of the Nakagami distribution.\nAlthough the distribution in Eq. ( 44 ) is naturally derived from the energy function in Eq. ( 35 ), these relationships to the Rice and Nakagami distributions suggest its appropriateness, given their widespread application in Telecommunications Engineering.\n\nWhen \\sigma^{2}=2, \\alpha=\\frac{k}{2} and k>0, Eq. ( 44 ) can be rewritten as the noncentral chi distribution:\n\n\\displaystyle p\\Bigl(r;\\nu,2,\\frac{k}{2}\\Bigr)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{2^{1-\\frac{k}{2}}\\,r^{k-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}+\\nu^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{0}(\\nu\\,r)}{\\Gamma(\\frac{k}{2})\\,L_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(-\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})}\n\n (47) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto r^{k-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{0}(\\nu\\,r),\n\n (48) \n\nwhere the noncentral chi distribution is given by\n\n\\displaystyle\\chi^{\\prime}(r;k,\\nu)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\nu^{1-\\frac{k}{2}}\\,r^{\\frac{k}{2}}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}+\\nu^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(\\nu\\,r)\n\n (49) \n\n\\displaystyle\\propto r^{\\frac{k}{2}}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}\\,I_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(\\nu\\,r)\n\n (50) \n\nfor k=2 (in this case, it is the Rician distribution as well).\nNote that the order of the modified Bessel function is always 0 in Eq. ( 44 ) (i.e., I_{0}), while that of the noncentral chi distribution depends on the exponent of r.\nThis difference is more apparent by rewriting Eq. ( 50 ) as\n\n\\displaystyle\\chi^{\\prime}(r;k,\\nu)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2}}(\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})^{n}}{n!}\\,\\frac{r^{2n+k-1}\\,{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}}{2^{n+\\frac{k}{2}-1}\\,\\Gamma(n+\\frac{k}{2})}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}{\\rm Poisson}\\Bigl(n;\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2}\\Bigr)\\,\\chi\\bigl(r;2n+k\\bigr),\n\n (51) \n\nwhere {\\rm Poisson}(\\,\\cdot\\,;\\lambda) is the Poisson distribution, \\chi(\\,\\cdot\\,;k) is the chi distribution, and I_{\\frac{k}{2}-1}(x)=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{1}{n!\\,\\Gamma(n+\\frac{k}{2})}(\\frac{x}{2})^{2n+\\frac{k}{2}-1} is used.\nIt indicates that the noncentral chi distribution is a mixture distribution of the chi distribution whose parameter n is determined by the Poisson distribution.\nOn the other hand, Eq. ( 47 ) can be rewritten as\n\n\\displaystyle p(r;\\nu,2,\\frac{k}{2})\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{(\\frac{k}{2})_{n}\\,(\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})^{n}}{n!^{2}\\,L_{-\\frac{k}{2}}(\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2})}\\,\\frac{r^{2n+k-1}\\,{\\rm e}^{-\\frac{r^{2}}{2}}}{2^{n+\\frac{k}{2}-1}\\,\\Gamma(n+\\frac{k}{2})}\n\n\\displaystyle=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}{\\rm Poisson^{\\prime}}\\Bigl(n;\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{2},\\frac{k}{2}\\Bigr)\\,\\chi\\bigl(r;2n+k\\bigr),\n\n (52) \n\nwhere (\\cdot)_{n} is the Pochhammer symbol,\n\n\\displaystyle{\\rm Poisson^{\\prime}}(n;\\lambda,\\alpha)=\\frac{(\\alpha)_{n}\\,\\lambda^{n}}{n!^{2}\\,L_{-\\alpha}(\\lambda)},\n\n (53) \n\nand I_{0}(x)=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{1}{n!\\,\\Gamma(n+1)}(\\frac{x}{2})^{2n} is used.\nThe modified Poisson distribution in Eq. ( 53 ) is skewed according to the parameter \\alpha, where \\alpha=1 reduces to the Poisson distribution.\nTherefore, the noncentral chi distribution and Eq. ( 44 ) can be interpreted as the marginal distribution of a chi distribution whose degrees of freedom are incremented by a random non-negative integer obaying the discrete (Poisson or modified Poisson) distributions.\n\nFurthermore, by writing the inverse variance (rate) and noncentrality as \\beta=\\frac{1}{\\sigma^{2}}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{>0} and \\lambda=\\frac{\\nu^{2}}{\\sigma^{2}}=\\beta\\,|\\mu|^{2}\\in\\mathbb{R}_{\\geq 0}, respectively, and viewing as a distribution for power x=r^{2}, Eq. ( 44 ) can be rewritten as\n\n\\displaystyle p(x;\\alpha,\\beta,\\lambda)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{\\beta^{\\alpha}}{\\Gamma(\\alpha)\\,L_{-\\alpha}(\\lambda)}\\,x^{\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta x}\\,I_{0}(2\\sqrt{\\beta\\,\\lambda\\,x}),\n\n (54) \n\nwhich reduces to the gamma distribution,\n\n\\displaystyle{\\rm Gamma}(x;\\alpha,\\beta)\n\n\\displaystyle=\\frac{\\beta^{\\alpha}}{\\Gamma(\\alpha)}\\,x^{\\alpha-1}\\,\\mathrm{e}^{-\\beta x},\n\n (55) \n\nwhen \\lambda=0.\nTherefore, Eq. ( 44 ) is also a generalization of the gamma distribution.\nIn other words, the gamma distribution can be viewed as a distribution of magnitude of PW-NCCG centered at the origin (\\lambda=\\nu=\\mu=0).\nUsing the modified Poisson distribution in Eq. ( 53 ), Eq. ( 54 ) can be written as\n\n\\displaystyle p(x;\\alpha,\\beta,\\lambda)=\\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}{\\rm Poisson^{\\prime}}(n;\\lambda,\\alpha)\\,{\\rm Gamma}(x;n+\\alpha,\\beta),\n\n (56) \n\nwhich indicates that the proposed distribution can be interpreted as a mixture distribution of the gamma and modified Poisson distributions.\nAlthough the distributions for magnitude in Eq. ( 44 ) and for power in Eq. ( 54 ) are essentially the same, we will only consider Eq. ( 54 ) hereafter because of its simplicity.\nFurther statistical properties of this distribution, such as the mean, variance, and kurtosis, as well as detailed comparisons are provided in [ 25 ] .\n\n IV PolarRBM and LogPolarRBM \n\nSimilar to standard BMs, the representational capacity of PolarBM can be significantly enhanced by introducing hidden units.", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
